\begin_layout Section
Nonlinear Systems and Equilibrium Points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A nonlinear system can be represented by a differential equation such as
 the on given by Equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{\dot{x}}=\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)\label{eq:general-nonlinear-system}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is the state vector and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}$
\end_inset

 is a nonlinear vector function, both of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of states of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

).
 It should be noted, however, that Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general-nonlinear-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 does not explicitly depend on the control variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

 although it still can represent the closed-loop dynamics of a control system
 if the input 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}$
\end_inset

 is dependent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general-nonlinear-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be rewritten to explicitly depend on the control input as shown in
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general-nonlinear-system-with-u"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and the closed-loop dynamics given in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general-nonlinear-system-with-g"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 ,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{\dot{x}}= & \,\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x},\boldsymbol{u},t\right)\label{eq:general-nonlinear-system-with-u}\\
\mathbf{\dot{x}}= & \,\mathbf{f}\left[\mathbf{x},\boldsymbol{g}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right),t\right]\label{eq:general-nonlinear-system-with-g}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}=\boldsymbol{g}\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The dynamics of linear systems can be written in the form given by Equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general-linear-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{\dot{x}}=\mathbf{A}\left(t\right)\mathbf{x}\label{eq:general-linear-system}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 being an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Autonomous and Non-Autonomous Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Autonomous and non-autonomous systems are the generalized versions of time-invar
iant and time-varying systems found in linear systems.
 A system is autonomous if it does not explicitly depend on time (otherwise
 it is non-autonomous) as shown in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general-autonomous-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{\dot{x}}=\mathbf{f}\left(\mathbf{x}\right).\label{eq:general-autonomous-system}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All systems are non-autonomous, because no dynamic characteristics are time-inva
riant.
 It's also important to note that the above definition is made on the closed-loo
p dynamics for control systems.
 The non-autonomous nature of the system can either be due to the time-varying
 nature of the plant or the control law (the book gives an example of 
\begin_inset Formula $u=-x^{2}\sin\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

).
 Fundamentally, the difference between autonomous and non-autonomous systems
 is the dependence on the initial time of the state trajectory for non-autonomou
s systems.
 This means that, for non-autonomous systems, the initial time must be considere
d for stability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium Points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:autonomous-system-equilibrium-point"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\emph on
equilibrium point 
\emph default
(or 
\emph on
state
\emph default
) if once 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\left(t\right)=\boldsymbol{x}^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 stays at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}$
\end_inset

 for all remaining time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}$
\end_inset

, Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:equilibrium-point"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is used
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{0}=\boldsymbol{f}\left(\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\right).\label{eq:equilibrium-point}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Linear time-invariant (LTI) systems have one equilibrium point at the origin
 if the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular.
 LTI systems have infinite equilibrium points in the null-space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 if it is singular.
 Nonlinear systems can have several to infinitely many equilibrium points.
 Equilibrium points for linear and nonlinear systems can be transformed
 to the origin which can make analysis easier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nominal Motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes we are concerned with the stability of a system to its original
 trajectory if subjected to slight perturbation (motion stability).
 This motion stability can be transformed to an equivalent stability problem
 about an equilibrium point, but the equivalent system will then be autonomous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 be a solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\dot{x}}=\boldsymbol{f}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 with initial value 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\left(t\right)=\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\left(0\right)=\boldsymbol{x}_{0}+\delta\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 be a perturbation of the initial condition.
 The error associated with the variation of the motion error is given in
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:variation-of-motion-error"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{e}\left(t\right)=\boldsymbol{x}\left(t\right)-\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\left(t\right).\label{eq:variation-of-motion-error}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 are solutions to Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general-autonomous-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and therefore we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\dot{\boldsymbol{x}}^{*}=\boldsymbol{f}\left(\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\right) & \qquad\boldsymbol{x}\left(0\right)=\boldsymbol{x}_{0}\\
\dot{\boldsymbol{x}}=\boldsymbol{f}\left(\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\right) & \qquad\boldsymbol{x}\left(0\right)=\boldsymbol{x}_{0}+\delta\boldsymbol{x}_{0}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the non-autonomous differential equation found in Equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{\boldsymbol{e}}\left(t\right)=\boldsymbol{f}\left(\boldsymbol{x}^{*}+\boldsymbol{e},t\right)-\boldsymbol{f}\left(\boldsymbol{x}^{*},t\right)=\boldsymbol{g}\left(\boldsymbol{e},t\right)\label{eq:error-differential-equation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 with initial conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}\left(0\right)=\delta\boldsymbol{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 .
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{g}\left(\boldsymbol{0},t\right)=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 , the equilibrium of the new system is at the origin and is non-autonomous
 due to the presence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Concepts of Stability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nonlinear systems may exhibit much more complex and exotic behavior than
 linear systems and, therefore, different stability concepts are needed
 to describe them.
 More concepts to describe this behavior such as asymptotic stability, exponenti
al stability, and global asymptotic stability will be introduced for for
 autonomous systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{R}$
\end_inset

 be a spherical region defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\right\Vert <R$
\end_inset

 in state-space and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{S}_{R}$
\end_inset

 be the sphere itself defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\right\Vert =R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stability and Instability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:verbose-lyapunov-stability"

\end_inset

The equilibrium state 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
stable
\emph default
 if, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $R>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists r>0$
\end_inset

 such that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\left(0\right)\right\Vert <r$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\left(t\right)\right\Vert <R$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall t\in\left[0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
unstable
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Stability (a.k.a.
 
\emph on
Lyapunov stability
\emph default
) means that the system trajectory can be kept arbitrarily close (
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

) to the origin by starting sufficiently close (
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

) to it.
 Definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:verbose-lyapunov-stability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be written as shown in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lyapunov-magnitude-definition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\forall\,R>0,\,\exists\,r>0,\;\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\left(0\right)\right\Vert <r\quad\Rightarrow\quad\forall\,t\geq0,\;\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\left(t\right)\right\Vert <R\label{eq:lyapunov-magnitude-definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or, as in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lyapunov-set-definition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\forall\,R>0,\,\exists\,r>0,\;\boldsymbol{x}\left(0\right)\in\boldsymbol{B}_{r}\quad\Rightarrow\quad\forall\,t\geq0,\;\boldsymbol{x}\left(t\right)\in\boldsymbol{B}_{R}.\label{eq:lyapunov-set-definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

On the other hand, an 
\emph on
unstable
\emph default
 equilibrium is one if 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\,\boldsymbol{B}_{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\,r>0$
\end_inset

, the trajectory can start in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{r}$
\end_inset

 and leave 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Asymptotic Stability and Exponential Stability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For many applications, Lyapunov stability may not be sufficient.
 For example, it is desired to not only know whether or not a satellite
 will maintain its attitude within a given range, but to also know if it
 will go back to its original attitude when disturbed.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:examples-of-different-types-of-stabilities"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows three types of stability that equilibrium points can be: trajectory
 1 is unstable, trajectory 2 is asymptotically stable, and trajectory 3
 is marginally stable where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{S}_{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{S}_{R}$
\end_inset

 are the spheres with radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:asymptotically-stable"

\end_inset

An equilibrium point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
asymptotically stable
\emph default
 if it's stable and 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\,r>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\left(0\right)\right\Vert <r$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\left(t\right)\rightarrow\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Basically, what Definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:asymptotically-stable"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is saying that the equilibrium is stable and states that start close to
 the equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 will converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 as time goes to infinity.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:examples-of-different-types-of-stabilities"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, trajectories 2 starts within the sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{S}_{r}$
\end_inset

 and eventually converges to the equilibrium labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This region 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{S}_{r}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\emph on
domain of attraction
\emph default
 of the equilibrium point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The domain of attraction is the largest region such that all trajectories
 initiated in it will eventually converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\emph on
marginally stable
\emph default
 equilibrium point is a Lyapunov stable equilibrium point that is not asymptotic
ally stable (e.g., trajectory 3).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\infty$
\end_inset

 then it is called 
\emph on
global
\emph default
 asymptotic stability (see Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:local-and-global-stability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

