\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:exponential-stability"

\end_inset

The equilibrium point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
exponentially stable
\emph default
 if there exists two strictly positive numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\forall\,t>0,\quad\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\left(t\right)\right\Vert \leq\alpha\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\left(0\right)\right\Vert \mathrm{e}^{-\lambda t}\label{eq:exponentially-stable-definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in some ball 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{r}$
\end_inset

 around the origin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, for an exponentially stable system the state vector converges
 to the origin faster than an exponential function (
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the rate of exponential convergence).
 With exponential stability, not only do you know where the state goes (to
 the equilibrium point) but you also know how fast it goes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Local and Global Stability
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:local-and-global-stability"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we've been discussing the local behavior of systems which is concerned
 with how the state evolves after starting near the equilibrium point.
 But what about if the state doesn't start near the equilibrium point? Local
 stability does little to tell us how the system will behave in this condition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:global-stability"

\end_inset

If asymptotic or exponential stability holds for 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 initial states, the equilibrium point is asymptotically (or exponentially)
 stable 
\emph on
in the large
\emph default
 (or, 
\emph on
globally
\emph default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
LTI systems are either asymptotically stable, marginally stable, or unstable.
 This is because linear asymptotic stability is both asymptotic and exponential.
 If the system is unstable it blows up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linearization and Local Stability
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:linearization-and-local-stability"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lyanpunov's linearization method is concerned with the local stability of
 a nonlinear system is the fundamental justification for using linear control
 techniques.
 It shows that stable the stability of the original physical system locally
 is guaranteed by linear control.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's assume that the autonomous system in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general-autonomous-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is continuously differentiable.
 The system can then be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{\boldsymbol{x}}=\boldsymbol{f}\left(\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{f}}{\partial\boldsymbol{x}}\right)_{\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{0}}\boldsymbol{x}+\boldsymbol{f}_{\text{h.o.t.}}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\label{eq:autonomous-system-taylor-expansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}_{\text{h.o.t.}}$
\end_inset

 is the higher-order-terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 of the Taylor expansion.
 The Jacobian matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 can be written as a constant matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 (shown in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linearized-system-jacobian"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) giving the linearized system about the equilibrium point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

, found in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linearized-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{A}= & \left(\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{f}}{\partial\boldsymbol{x}}\right)_{\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{0}}\label{eq:linearized-system-jacobian}\\
\dot{\boldsymbol{x}}= & \,\boldsymbol{A}\boldsymbol{x}\label{eq:linearized-system}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which, of course, is ignoring the higher-order-terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}_{\text{h.o.t.}}$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:lyapunovs-linearization-method"

\end_inset

Lyapunov's linearization method
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If the linearized system is strictly stable (i.e., all the eigenvalues of
 
\shape italic

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 are strictly in the left-half complex plane), then the equilibrium point
 is asymptotically stable (for the actual nonlinear system).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the linearized system is unstable (i.e., if at least on eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 is in the right-half complex plane), then the equilibrium point is unstable
 (for the nonlinear system).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the linearized system is marginally stable (i.e., all eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 are in the left-half complex plane but at least one lies on the 
\begin_inset Formula $j\omega$
\end_inset

 axis), then one cannot conclude anything from the linear approximation
 (the equilibrium point may be stable, asymptotically stable, or unstable
 for the nonlinear system).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section
Lyapunov's Direct Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the total energy of a system continuously dissipates then it must settle
 to an equilibrium point.
 This applies to both linear and nonlinear systems.
 Therefore, stability of a system may be concluded by examining a single
 scalar function, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 There are relations between mechanical energy and stability:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
zero energy corresponds to an equilibrium point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
asymptotic stability corresponds to mechanical energy going to zero
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
instability corresponds to the growth of mechanical energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic method is to generate a scalar function, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

, that is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

energy-like
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the dynamic system and examine the time-variation (
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}$
\end_inset

) of that function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Positive Definite Functions and Lyapunov Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 has two properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it is strictly positive unless 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\boldsymbol{x}}$
\end_inset

 are both zero (positive definite)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it is monotonically increasing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:locally-positive-definite"

\end_inset

A scalar continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
locally positive definite
\emph default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{0}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and, in a ball 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{R_{0}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{x}\neq\boldsymbol{0}\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)>0\label{eq:locally-positive-definite-definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{0}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and the above property holds over the whole state-space then 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
globally positive definite
\emph default
.
\end_layout

