\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 actually represents an implicit function of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and its derivative with respect to time can be found (assuming that it
 is differentiable) by the chain rule and shown in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lyapunov-function-time-derivative"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{V}=\frac{dV\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)}{dt}=\frac{\partial V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)}{\partial\boldsymbol{x}}\,\dot{\boldsymbol{x}}=\frac{\partial V}{\partial\boldsymbol{x}}\,\boldsymbol{f}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right).\label{eq:lyapunov-function-time-derivative}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

