\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium Point Theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lyapunov Theorem for Local Stability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:lyapunov-local-stability"

\end_inset

If, in a ball 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{R_{0}}$
\end_inset

, there exists a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 with continuous first partial derivatives such that
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is positive definite (locally in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{R_{0}}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is negative semi-definite (locally in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{R_{0}}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then the equilibrium point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 is stable.
 If, actually the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is locally negative definite in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{R_{0}}$
\end_inset

, then the stability is asymptotic.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Let's look at a couple of examples.
 First, let's examine local stability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Local Stability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The dynamics of a damped pendulum is given in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-dynamics-of-damped-pendulum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{\theta}+\dot{\theta}+\sin\theta=0.\label{eq:example-dynamics-of-damped-pendulum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
A possible Lyapunov function is one that is a combination of the kinetic
 and potential energies, given in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-damped-pendulum-lyapunov-function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=\left(1-\cos\theta\right)+\frac{\dot{\theta}^{2}}{2}.\label{eq:example-damped-pendulum-lyapunov-function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let's verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is locally positive definite.
 This can be done by examining the time-derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

, noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the power dissipation and is shown in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-damped-pendulum-vdot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{V}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=\dot{\theta}\sin\theta+\dot{\theta}\ddot{\theta}=-\dot{\theta}^{2}\leq0.\label{eq:example-damped-pendulum-vdot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Because Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-damped-pendulum-vdot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 represents the power dissipation of the system and it is always negative
 we can conclude that the system is stable because the energy will eventually
 go to zero.
 Because Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-damped-pendulum-vdot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is only negative semi-definite, we cannot say anything about the systems
 asymptotic stability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, let's examine asymptotic stability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Asymptotic Stability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let a nonlinear system be defined by Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-asymptotic-stability-nonlinear-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\dot{x}_{1}= & \,x_{1}\left(x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}-2\right)-4x_{1}x_{2}^{2}\nonumber \\
\dot{x}_{2}= & \,4x_{1}^{2}x_{2}+x_{2}\left(x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}-2\right)\label{eq:example-asymptotic-stability-nonlinear-system}
\end{align}

\end_inset

around its equilibrium point at the origin.
 Let the positive definite function in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-asymptotic-stability-lyapunov"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 be the Lyapunov function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}.\label{eq:example-asymptotic-stability-lyapunov}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The time-derivative for Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-asymptotic-stability-lyapunov"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is given in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-asymptotic-stability-vdot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{V}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=2\left(x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}\right)\left(x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}-2\right)\label{eq:example-asymptotic-stability-vdot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is locally negative definite in the region 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}<2$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the origin is asymptotically stable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lyapunov Theorem for Global Stability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a system to have 
\emph on
global
\emph default
 stability, the radius of the ball 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}_{R_{0}}$
\end_inset

 must be extended to infinity and 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 must be 
\emph on
radially bounded
\emph default
.
 To be radially bounded, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\right\Vert \rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 tends to infinity in any direction).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Global Stability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Assume that there exists a scalar function 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

, with continuous first order derivatives such that
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is positive definite
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is negative definite
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\right\Vert \rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is radially bounded)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then the equilibrium at the origin is globally asymptotically stable.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The reason that 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 needs to be radially bounded is so that the contours 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=V_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:example-locally-positive-definite-lyapunov-contour-plot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the contour plot for the Lyapunov function, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

, found in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-locally-positive-definite-lyapunov-function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The contour lines of this 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 are not all closed which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is not radially bounded system and the system is only locally stable, not
 globally.
 If all of the contour curves were closed , then it would not be possible
 for state trajectories to drift away from the equilibrium point.
\end_layout

