\begin_layout Subsection
Invariant Set Theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous theorems can be difficult to apply to show asymptotic stability,
 often because 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 of the candidate Lyapunov function is negative semi-definite.
 Despite this, it's still possible to show asymptotic stability using the
 invariant set theorems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:invariant-set"

\end_inset

A set 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\emph on
invariant set
\emph default
 for a dynamic system if every system trajectory which starts from a point
 in 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset


\series default
 remains in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset

 for all future time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is motivated in part by the fact that requiring 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 to be negative definite is too strong and to show more general behaviors
 such as convergence to limit cycles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Local Invariant Set Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Local Invariant Set Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Consider an autonomous system of the form found in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general-autonomous-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}$
\end_inset

 continuous and let 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 be a scalar function with continuous first partial derivatives.
 Assume that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for some 
\begin_inset Formula $l>0$
\end_inset

, the region 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}_{l}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)<l$
\end_inset

 is bounded
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\leq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}_{l}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all points within 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}_{l}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{M}$
\end_inset

 be the largest invariant set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, every solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 originating in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}_{l}$
\end_inset

 tends to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{M}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{M}$
\end_inset

 is the union of all invariant sets (e.g., equilibrium points or limit cycles)
 within 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}$
\end_inset

 is the invariant set then 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{M}=\boldsymbol{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Although 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is still referred to as the Lyapunov function it is no longer required
 to be positive definite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Attractive Limit Cycle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let's examine the system given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\dot{x}_{1}= & x_{2}-x_{1}^{7}\left[x_{1}^{4}+2x_{2}^{2}-10\right]\\
\dot{x}_{2}= & -x_{1}^{3}-3x_{2}^{5}\left[x_{1}^{4}+2x_{2}^{2}-10\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dt}\left[x_{1}^{4}+2x_{2}^{2}-10\right]=-\left(4x_{1}^{10}+12x_{2}^{6}\right)\left[x_{1}^{4}+2x_{2}^{2}-10\right]$
\end_inset

, therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x_{1}^{4}+2x_{2}^{2}-10\right]$
\end_inset

 is an invariant set.
 The motion on this set can be described by either 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\dot{x}_{1}= & \,x_{2}\\
\dot{x}_{2}= & -x_{1}^{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which, means that the invariant set is a limit cycle that rotates clockwise.
 The attractiveness of the limit cylce can be determined by choosing the
 candidate Lyapunov function to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\left(x_{1}^{4}+2x_{2}^{2}-10\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset

which is the distance to the limit cycle.
 It can be seen that for any arbitrarily chosen positive number 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 the region surrounding the limit cycle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}_{l}$
\end_inset

, is bounded.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{V}=-8\left(x_{1}^{10}+3x_{2}^{6}\right)\left(x_{1}^{4}+2x_{2}^{2}-10\right)
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}$
\end_inset

 is negative everywhere except if 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}=0$
\end_inset

, namely
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{1}^{4}+2x_{2}^{2}=10\qquad\text{or}\qquad x_{1}^{10}+3x_{2}^{6}=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The first equation represents the equation of the motion of the limit cycle
 and the second is only true at the origin.
 This means that the system has two invariant sets: the limit cycle and
 the origin.
 Therefore, the invariant set of the system is the union of both sets.
 It should be noted that the equilibrium point at the origin is unstable
 and only trajectories starting there will converge to the origin, all others
 tend to the limit cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cor:local-invariant-set"

\end_inset

Consider the autonomous system found in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general-autonomous-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{f}$
\end_inset

 continuous and let 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 be a scalar function with continuous first partial derivatives.
 Assume that in a certain neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 of the origin
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is locally positive definite
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}$
\end_inset

 is negative semi-definite
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{R}$
\end_inset

