\begin_layout Subsection
Brief Linear Algebra Review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A square matrix is 
\emph on
symmetric
\emph default
 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{T}=M$
\end_inset

 and a matrix is 
\emph on
skew-symmetric
\emph default
 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{T}=-M$
\end_inset

.
 Any square matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M & =\frac{M+M^{T}}{2}+\frac{M-M^{T}}{2}\\
 & =\frac{M_{\text{sym}}}{2}+\frac{M_{\text{skew}}}{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\text{sym}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\text{skew}}$
\end_inset

 are symmetric and skew-symmetric matrices, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is skew-symmetric.
 Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{x}^{T}M\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{x}M^{T}\boldsymbol{x}^{T}=-\boldsymbol{x}^{T}M\boldsymbol{x}\quad\forall\boldsymbol{x}
\]

\end_inset

 which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{T}M\boldsymbol{x}=0,\;\forall\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quadratic functions of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{T}M\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a square matrix) can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{T}M_{\text{sym}}\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

.
 A square matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is positive definite (
\begin_inset Formula $M>0)$
\end_inset

 if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{x}\neq\boldsymbol{0}\quad\Rightarrow\quad\boldsymbol{x}^{T}M\boldsymbol{x}>0
\]

\end_inset

which implies that to every positive definite matrix is associated a positive
 definite function, though the converse is not necessarily true.
 Sylvester's theorem shows that if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is symmetric, it is necessary for all of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

's eigenvalues to be strictly positive for 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to be positive definite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lyapunov Analysis of Linear Time-Invariant Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a linear system of the form given in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general-linear-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, a candidate Lyapunov function of quadratic form is given in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:quadratic-lyapunov-for-linear-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V=\boldsymbol{x}^{T}\boldsymbol{P}\boldsymbol{x}\label{eq:quadratic-lyapunov-for-linear-system}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 is a given symmetric positive definite matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 is strictly stable.
 The time-derivative is given in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:quadratic-lyaponov-for-linear-system-time-derivative"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\dot{V}= & \,\boldsymbol{\dot{x}}^{T}\boldsymbol{P}\boldsymbol{x}+\boldsymbol{x}^{T}\boldsymbol{\dot{P}}\boldsymbol{x}+\boldsymbol{x}^{T}\boldsymbol{P}\dot{\boldsymbol{x}}\nonumber \\
= & \,\boldsymbol{\dot{x}}^{T}\boldsymbol{P}\boldsymbol{x}+\boldsymbol{x}^{T}\boldsymbol{P}\dot{\boldsymbol{x}}\nonumber \\
= & \,\boldsymbol{x}^{T}\boldsymbol{A}^{T}\boldsymbol{P}\boldsymbol{x}+\boldsymbol{x}^{T}\boldsymbol{P}\boldsymbol{A}\boldsymbol{x}\nonumber \\
= & -\boldsymbol{x}^{T}\boldsymbol{Q}\boldsymbol{x}.\label{eq:quadratic-lyaponov-for-linear-system-time-derivative}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question that we want to answer is, given a symmetric positive definite
 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 and a strictly stable system (given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

), can we find a positive definite matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}$
\end_inset

 that is also symmetric positive definite? A counter example will show that
 the answer is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider a second-order linear system whose 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{A}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 4\\
-8 & -12
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}=\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\boldsymbol{Q}=\boldsymbol{A}^{T}\boldsymbol{P}+\boldsymbol{P}\boldsymbol{A}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 4\\
-8 & -12
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

 which is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 positive definite.
 Therefore, we cannot use any given symmetric positive definite 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 to find a positive definite 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What can be done, however, is to go the other way around: start with a given
 symmetric positive definite 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}$
\end_inset

 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 from using the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $-\boldsymbol{Q}=\boldsymbol{A}^{T}\boldsymbol{P}+\boldsymbol{P}\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 and to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 is positive definite.
 This method will always lead to conclusive results for stable linear systems,
 as shown in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:necessary-and-sufficient-condition-strictly-stable-lti-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:necessary-and-sufficient-condition-strictly-stable-lti-system"

\end_inset

A necessary and sufficient condition for an LTI system 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\dot{x}=}\boldsymbol{A}\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 to be strictly stable is that, for any symmetric positive definite 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}$
\end_inset

, the unique matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $-\boldsymbol{Q}=\boldsymbol{A}^{T}\boldsymbol{P}+\boldsymbol{P}\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 be symmetric positive definite.
\end_layout

